<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08033a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08033a">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08033a"> 33(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Jack Barry father USA Navy / W<sup>m</sup> Brown &#x3003; Argen&mdash;/ O&apos;Higgins &mdash; Chile</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>The Wild Geese / Mayo Man Father of the Argentine Navy</b> The project of erecting in Foxford, Co. Mayo, a hall to commemorate the birth there of Admiral <mark>Wm. Brown, father of the Argentine Navy</mark>, is being generously supported by Irish exiles, both in this country and the Argentine. / <mark>Chile</mark> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> also acknowledges an Irishman as the founder of her Navy, and up to the &ldquo;nineties&rdquo; of the last century always named one of her warships the Almirante Lynch in his honour.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> there is still an O&apos;Higgins among the cruisers, named after the liberator, General <mark>O&apos;Higgins</mark>, son of the Galway man who was Spain&apos;s last Viceroy in the Pacific Republic. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Of course everybody knows the story of Commodore <mark>Jack Barry, the father of the United States Navy</mark>. <small> <a name="FJ29dec23" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FJ29dec23"><cite title="source">Freeman's Journal</cite></a> (29 December 1923) 5/3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: John Barry (1745-1803), a distinguished Irish-American naval officer known as &lsquo;Father of the American Navy&rsquo;. William Brown (1777-1857), admiral in Argentinean navy, who fought against the Spanish and the Brazilians. Bernardo O&apos;Higgins (1778-1842) was father of Chilean Independence; his (Irish) father was Viceroy of Peru. </mm> </dd></dl>
